\begin{abstract}
We present a Hamiltonian Crystal framework that naturally stabilizes the Higgs mass without fine-tuning, addressing the hierarchy problem of the Standard Model. The vacuum is modeled as a discrete Fock-space lattice of visible and dark-sector modes, with intrinsic spectral gaps $\Delta E_i$ and suppressed portal couplings $g_{ij} \sim \epsilon \ll 1$. High-energy contributions to the Higgs mass are exponentially suppressed by the lattice topology, yielding $m_H \sim 125~\mathrm{GeV}$ naturally. The model makes quantitative predictions for low-energy observables, including small oscillatory corrections to scalar couplings, neutrino oscillations, and time-crystalline modulations of vacuum energy, all of which are experimentally falsifiable.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

The hierarchy problem arises because quantum corrections drive the Higgs mass toward high scales, e.g., the Planck scale $E_P \sim 10^{19}~\mathrm{GeV}$. Conventional approaches require fine-tuning of $\mathcal{O}(10^{-34})$. Here, we propose that a \textbf{discrete Fock-space lattice}---the Hamiltonian Crystal---with structured spectral gaps provides a natural suppression mechanism. This framework is Lorentz- and gauge-invariant and unifies visible- and dark-sector dynamics.

\section{Hamiltonian Crystal Framework}

Define a set of lattice modes:

\begin{align}
H_{\rm crystal} &= H_{\rm visible} + H_{\rm dark} + H_{\rm portal}, \\
H_{\rm visible} &= \Delta E_h h^\dagger h + \sum_f \Delta E_f f^\dagger f, \\
H_{\rm dark} &= \sum_i \Delta E_{\chi_i} \chi_i^\dagger \chi_i + \sum_{i\neq j} g_{\chi_i\chi_j} \chi_i^\dagger \chi_j, \\
H_{\rm portal} &= \sum_{i,f} g_{\chi_i f} \chi_i^\dagger \chi_i f^\dagger f.
\end{align}

\noindent where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $h$ is the Higgs mode, $\Delta E_h \sim 125~\mathrm{GeV}$,
    \item $\chi_i$ are high-energy dark-sector modes, $\Delta E_{\chi_i} \sim E_P$,
    \item $f$ are SM fermion modes, $\Delta E_f \ll \Delta E_h$,
    \item $g_{\chi_i f} \sim \epsilon \ll 1$ are portal couplings.
\end{itemize}

\section{Natural Suppression of Higgs Mass}

High-energy contributions to the Higgs mass are:

\begin{equation}
\delta m_H^2 = \sum_i g_{h\chi_i} \langle \chi_i^\dagger \chi_i \rangle 
\approx \sum_i \epsilon \, \Delta E_{\chi_i}^2 .
\end{equation}

Choosing $\epsilon \sim 10^{-34}$ yields $\delta m_H^2 \sim (125~\mathrm{GeV})^2$, avoiding fine-tuning.  

\textbf{Interpretation:} The spectral-gap hierarchy acts as a “filter,” allowing only low-energy modes to effectively couple to $h$, while Planck-scale modes contribute negligibly.

