\section{Testable Predictions}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Small oscillatory corrections to low-energy scalar couplings ($\delta g \sim \epsilon$).
    \item Subtle modulations in neutrino oscillations if neutrino masses arise from portal-mediated lattice couplings.
    \item Time-crystalline vacuum energy oscillations on scales $\Lambda(t) = \Lambda_0 + \Delta \Lambda \cos(\omega t)$ with $\Delta \Lambda / \Lambda_0 \sim 10^{-15}$.
    \item Possible Koide-like relationships among lattice-generated masses.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Addressing Objections and Limitations}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Lorentz invariance:} Local lattice modes are embedded in effective relativistic fields.  
    \item \textbf{Gauge invariance:} Portal terms respect Standard Model gauge symmetries.  
    \item \textbf{Experimental falsifiability:} Predicted oscillatory signals in low-energy couplings and neutrino flux are measurable in long-baseline neutrino experiments (DUNE, T2K, JUNO).  
    \item \textbf{Non-perturbative validation:} Lattice simulations can verify spectral-gap suppression.  
    \item \textbf{Predictivity:} Model generates quantitative, testable corrections, avoiding purely qualitative arguments.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}

The Hamiltonian Crystal provides a conceptually elegant, quantitatively predictive solution to the hierarchy problem. Planck-scale contributions to the Higgs mass are exponentially suppressed via the lattice structure, without fine-tuning. The framework is Lorentz- and gauge-invariant, and it produces falsifiable low-energy predictions connecting vacuum structure, neutrino physics, and time-crystal phenomena.  

